%T A396426 20,24,15,54,45,21,17,55,83,32,19,33,56,35,72,60,25,57,99,162,26,23,
%U A396426 164,61,16,243,47,48,245,87,62,89,168,101,59,88,163,84,14,34,90
%N A396426 Lexicographically earliest sequence of distinct nonnegative integers whose ternary plot has no two pixels within a knights' move's distance of a knight of the opposing color.
%C A396426 A version of A394166 with two opposing knights; also inspired by A392177.
%C A396426 For any k >= 0, the first term >= 3^k is a power of three or twice a power of three.
%C A396426 Is the sequence a permutation of the nonnegative integers?
%C A396426 Let q(m) be the number of ternary digits of m. If m is not in the sequence then c*3^q(m) + m is not in the sequence for c >= 0. - _David A. Corneth_, May 26 2026
%H A396426 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A396426/b396426.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A396426 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A396426/a396426.txt">Table of n, a(n), ternary(a(n)) with dots instead of zeros for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A396426 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A396426/a396426.py.txt">Python program for OEIS A396426</a>
%H A396426 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A396426/a396426.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%e A396426 The first terms, alongside their ternary expansions with dots instead of zeros, are:
%e A396426   n   a(n)  ternary(a(n))
%e A396426   --  ----  -------------
%e A396426    0     0              .
%e A396426    1     1              1
%e A396426    2     2              2
%e A396426    3     3             1.
%e A396426    4     6             2.
%e A396426    5     4             11
%e A396426    6     5             12
%e A396426    7    27           1...
%e A396426    8     9            1..
%e A396426    9     7             21
%e A396426   10    10            1.1
%e A396426   11    30           1.1.
%e A396426   12    11            1.2
%e A396426   13    28           1..1
%e A396426   14    29           1..2
%e A396426   15    31           1.11
%e A396426   16    36           11..
